# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1784-british-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The **1708 British general election** was the first general election to be held after the Acts of Union had united the Parliaments of England and Scotland.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The election saw the Whigs gain a majority in the House of Commons, and by November the Whig-dominated parliament had succeeded in pressuring the Queen into accepting the Whig Junto into government for the first time since the late 1690s.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The Whigs only able to take partial control of the government, however, owing to the continued presence of the moderate Tory Godolphin in the cabinet (as Lord High Treasurer) and the opposition of the Queen.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] Contests were held in 95 of the 269 English and Welsh constituencies and 28 of the 45 Scottish constituencies.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] Following the election, Whig MP Lord Somers was appointed as Lord President of the Council.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] However, moderate Tory Lord Godolphin remained as Lord High Treasurer and the Godolphin–Marlborough ministry remained in place.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In England, there were 513 MPs elected from 245 constituencies (203 boroughs, 40 counties, and 2 universities).
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In Wales, there were 24 MPs from 24 constituencies.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In Scotland, there were 45 MPs from 45 constituencies (30 counties and 15 burghs).
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The first general election held since the Union took place between 30 April 1708 and 7 July 1708.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] At this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In England and Wales, the Whigs took 268 seats and the Tories took 225, with 20 unclassified.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The 45 in Scotland could be classified as ministerial supporters.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The **1710 British general election** produced a landslide victory for the Tories.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The election came in the wake of the prosecution of Henry Sacheverell, which had led to the collapse of the previous government led by Godolphin and the Whig Junto.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] In November 1709 the clergyman Henry Sacheverell had delivered a sermon fiercely criticising the government's policy of toleration for Protestant dissenters and attacking the personal conduct of the ministers.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The government had Sacheverell impeached, and he was narrowly found guilty but received only a light sentence, making the government appear weak and vindictive.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The trial enraged a large section of the population, and riots in London led to attacks on dissenting places of worship and cries of "Church in Danger".
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The government's unpopularity was further increased by its enthusiasm for the war with France, as peace talks with the French king Louis XIV had broken down over the government's insistence that the Bourbons hand over the Spanish throne to the Habsburgs.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The Tories' policy of pursuing peace appealed to a country worn out by constant war.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Queen Anne, disliking the Junto and sensing that the government could not survive long, gradually replaced it with a Tory ministry throughout the summer of 1710.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The election was bitterly contested in almost all the counties and "open" boroughs, even when a poll was not held.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Contests occurred in 131 constituencies in England and Wales; approximately half of all English and Welsh constituencies.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The overwhelming Tory victory surprised few, and following the election most remaining Whigs resigned from office.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The new government was led by the moderate Tory Robert Harley who was unpopular among the more partisan Tories.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Harley's ministry faced increasing pressure from the extremists whose position in Parliament had been enormously strengthened by the result.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] See 1796 British general election for details.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The constituencies used were the same throughout the existence of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The general election was held between 2 October 1710 and 16 November 1710.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or parliamentary borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:1784-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The **1713 British general election** was held on 22 August 1713 to 12 November 1713, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] It produced further gains for the governing Tory party.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The government remained popular with the electorate, however, having entered into peace negotiations ending the War of the Spanish Succession and later agreeing on the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The Tories consequently made further gains against the Whigs, making Harley's job even more difficult.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] Contests were held in 94 constituencies in England and Wales, some 35 per cent of the total, reflecting a decline in partisan tension and the Whigs' belief that they were unlikely to win anyway.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 August 1713 and 12 November 1713.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The **1715 British general election** was held on 22 January 1715 to 9 March 1715, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] It returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 5th Parliament of Great Britain to be held, after the 1707 merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] In October 1714, soon after George I had arrived in London after ascending to the throne, he dismissed the Tory cabinet and replaced it with one almost entirely composed of Whigs, as they were responsible for securing his succession.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The election of 1715 saw the Whigs win an overwhelming majority in the House of Commons, and afterwards virtually all Tories in central or local government were purged, leading to a period of Whig ascendancy lasting almost fifty years during which Tories were almost entirely excluded from office.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The Whigs then moved to impeach Robert Harley, the former Tory first minister.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] After he was imprisoned in the Tower of London for two years, the case ultimately ended with his acquittal in 1717.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 January 1715 and 9 March 1715.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The **1722 British general election** elected members to serve in the House of Commons of the 6th Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] This was the fifth such election since the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Thanks to the Septennial Act 1715, which swept away the maximum three-year life of a parliament created by the Meeting of Parliament Act 1694, it followed seven years after the previous election, that of 1715.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The election was fiercely fought, with contests taking place in more than half of the constituencies, which was unusual for the time.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] In the midst of the election, word came from France of a Jacobite plot aimed at an imminent coup d'état.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Led by Francis Atterbury, Bishop of Rochester, Lord North and Grey, and other Tory opponents of Walpole, this was later known as the "Atterbury Plot".
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Previously election results had broadly reflected the opinion of at least the minority of adult males who had the vote, although the system had always been subject to the influence of corruption and patronage.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] However, now that one-party government had been established, those influences could be used systematically to ensure the governing party's victory.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] This election set the pattern for much of the rest of the eighteenth century; as partisan feeling began to decline during the years of the Whig oligarchy, the rigging of elections became ever easier, so that British governments could almost always guarantee victory.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The general election was held between 19 March 1722 and 9 May 1722.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The **1727 British general election** returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 7th Parliament of Great Britain to be summoned, after the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The election was triggered by the death of King George I; at the time, it was the convention to hold new elections following the succession of a new monarch.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] A group known as the Patriot Whigs, led by William Pulteney, who were disenchanted with Robert Walpole's government and believed he was betraying Whig principles, had been formed prior to the election.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] Bolingbroke and Pulteney had not expected the next election to occur until 1729, and were consequently caught unprepared.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] They failed to make any gains against the government party.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The general election was held between 14 August 1727 and 17 October 1727.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] At this period, elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] The **1734 British general election** returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 8th Parliament of Great Britain to be summoned, after the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] Robert Walpole's increasingly unpopular Whig government lost ground to the Tories and the opposition Whigs, but still had a secure majority in the House of Commons.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] The Patriot Whigs under William Pulteney were joined in opposition by a group of Whig members led by Lord Cobham.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] They were known as the Cobhamites, or 'Cobham's Cubs'.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 April 1734 and 6 June 1734.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The **1784 British general election** resulted in William Pitt the Younger securing an overall majority of about 120 in the House of Commons of Great Britain, having previously had to survive in a House which was dominated by his opponents.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] In December 1783, George III engineered the dismissal of the Fox–North coalition, which he hated, and appointed William Pitt the Younger as Prime Minister.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Pitt had very little personal support in the House of Commons, and the supporters of Charles James Fox and Lord North felt that the constitution of the country had been violated.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The doctrine that the government must always have a majority in the House of Commons was not yet established and Fox knew he had to be careful.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Pitt remained in office, and government supporters ensured petitions and resolutions of borough corporations were presented to Parliament to encourage members to back Pitt, and slowly Members changed sides.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] By 1 March, Fox's motion which concluded by "beseech[ing] His Majesty, that He would be graciously pleased to lay the Foundation of a strong and stable Government, by the previous Removal of His present Ministers" was carried but only by 201 to 189.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] A week later, a more strongly worded motion threatening the withholding of supply was also passed—but only by 191 to 190.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Fox thereafter declined to push motions, as his base continued to crumble.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Pitt meanwhile decided to go to the country and on 24 March, Parliament was prorogued and on the following day the Parliament first elected in 1780 was dissolved.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The election was fought very much as a national campaign around the questions of the fall of the Fox–North government and whether or not Pitt should continue in office, rather than a series of local campaigns, which was more common for 18th century British elections.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Thanks to a combination of patronage and bribes paid by HM Treasury, many small pocket boroughs returned Pitt-supporting MPs as widely expected.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Additionally, in the constituencies decided by large electorates there was massive support for candidates who backed Pitt.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Many of Fox's supporters were forced either to withdraw or to make deals with their opponents to avoid electoral defeat.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] In the county constituencies only one Fox supporter was elected in a contest, although others returned due to local electoral pacts.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Those Members who had remained in opposition, refusing to go over to support Pitt, who failed to return to the House of Commons as a consequence, became known as "Fox's Martyrs" in reference to John Foxe's *Book of Martyrs* (although the majority were supporters of North).
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The first day's polling, 30 March, saw thirteen government supporters and four opponents returned.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] By the conclusion of the fifth day (3 April), there were already more than 150 government Members and a lead of fifty over the supporters of the coalition.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The government achieved an overall majority on 15 April and the election ended on 10 May.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The contests involving both Pitt and Fox attracted particular attention.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Pitt had long wished to be a Member of Parliament for the University of Cambridge and had failed to be elected when he stood for the seat in the 1780 general election.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Now he was returned at the top of the poll and would hold the seat for the rest of his life.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Fox was one of the two sitting members for the constituency of Westminster, which had the largest electorate of any in the country and a great deal of prestige.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] His position there was central to his claim to be representing the people.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Even George, Prince of Wales, campaigned for Fox.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] At the conclusion of polling on 17 May, Fox had narrowly succeeded, with 6,233 votes to Sir Cecil Wray's 5,998.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] However, Pitt's supporters then demanded a scrutiny of the votes and the Returning Officer therefore did not make the return.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] A scrutiny in a constituency as large as Westminster was an enormously time-consuming process; Fox, suspecting this might happen, had already arranged for his return for the Tain Burghs, which had elected him on 26 April, so that he would not be out of the House during such a scrutiny.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The process did not show unexpectedly large numbers of unqualified voters and as the months went by it looked more and more like a political delaying tactic; on 4 March 1785 the House of Commons finally put an end to it by ordering the Returning Officer to declare the result.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The election was notable for being one of the first in history in which visual propaganda, in the form of caricatures satirising or promoting the candidates, played a significant role.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Caricatures appeared almost daily, allowing the young artists Thomas Rowlandson and James Gillray both to make their names on the strength of their satirical output.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] After the election, one of the leading London print sellers, William Humphrey, gathered together a number of the election plates to illustrate a detailed blow-by-blow account of the election.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] A London constable, Nicholas Casson, was killed during the election.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The election results were originally recorded as being 490 votes for William Fowle Middleton, 297 votes for John Cator (Whig) and 7 votes for Charles Crickitt (Tory).
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] However, Crickitt filed a petition against Cator's election, accusing him of bribery.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] The petition was handled by Bamber Gascoyne, who was both Crickitt's political agent and godfather.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] John Strutt acted on Crickitt's behalf on the House of Commons committee which investigated the allegation.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Crickitt also had the support of the Duke of Cumberland.
[src:1784-british-general-election/1784-british-general-election] Cator's election was declared void and Crickett was seated in June 1784.
